---
name: python-best-practices.mdc
description: Best practices for Python programming
globs: **/*.py
---

- Use clear, descriptive names for variables and functions, following the convention of lowercase with underscores
- Maintain consistent indentation (4 spaces) and spacing throughout your code
- Break down complex functions into smaller, focused units to adhere to the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- Follow the principle of separation of concerns
- Keep functions concise, ideally under 20 lines, to enhance readability
- Utilize list comprehensions and generator expressions for concise and efficient data processing
- Implement proper error handling with try/except blocks, and use specific exception types when possible
- Leverage context managers (with statements) for resource management and to ensure proper cleanup
- Use type hints to improve code readability and catch potential type-related errors early
- Follow PEP 8 style guide for consistent code formatting and style
- Write comprehensive docstrings for modules, functions, and classes in google style notation to provide clear documentation
- Utilize virtual environments to manage project dependencies and avoid version conflicts
- Follow DRY, KISS, and SOLID principles where applicable
- Consider time and space complexity, using appropriate data structures and optimizing only when necessary
- Implement proper logging and write unit tests when applicable
- Use version control with descriptive commit messages
- Validate input requirements, consider security implications, and ensure maintainability
- Check for potential edge cases and verify backward compatibility
- Function names should be lowercase, with words separated by underscores as necessary to improve readability
- Variable names follow the same convention as function names
- mixedCase is allowed only in contexts where that's already the prevailing style (e.g. threading.py), to retain backwards compatibility
